  <data name="ElevationBanner_DismissTooltip" xml:space="preserve"><value>Dismiss for this session</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_Intro" xml:space="preserve"><value>Running Startup Groups as administrator unlocks the following. The app still works without it — these features silently no-op or route through a UAC prompt per action.</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_SilentService_Heading" xml:space="preserve"><value>Silent service control</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_SilentService_Body" xml:space="preserve"><value>Start and stop Windows services inside your groups without a UAC prompt for each action. Non-admin sessions fall back to a helper process that prompts once per operation.</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_Etw_Heading" xml:space="preserve"><value>ETW launch-dependency inference</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_Etw_Body" xml:space="preserve"><value>Uses Event Tracing for Windows (kernel sessions) to observe process starts, file opens, and network activity while a group launches, so the orchestrator can learn which app waits on which and sequence them more accurately next time. Kernel ETW providers require admin.</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_SystemStartup_Heading" xml:space="preserve"><value>System-wide startup management</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_SystemStartup_Body" xml:space="preserve"><value>Toggle and delete HKLM Run and Common startup folder entries on the Windows Startup page. Without admin those rows are read-only — you can see them but not change them.</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_ElevatedApps_Heading" xml:space="preserve"><value>Smoother handling of elevated apps</value></data>
  <data name="ElevationBanner_ElevatedApps_Body" xml:space="preserve"><value>Apps that themselves require admin (e.g. tools with an embedded manifest) can be launched, readiness-checked, and stopped without a UAC dialog interrupting the middle of a group sequence.</value></data>

